response:
The projection of a vector $\vec{v}$ onto a vector $\vec{u}$ is given by,  
$\operatorname{proj}_\vec{u} \vec{v} = \frac{\vec{u}\cdot \vec{v}}{\vec{u}\cdot \vec{u}} * \vec{u}.$</think> <answer>
\begin{align}
\operatorname{proj}_{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}} \vec{v}
&=  \frac{\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 7 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \vec{v}}{\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 7 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 7 \end{pmatrix}} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}
&= \frac{\vec{v}_1 + 7\vec{v}_2}{1 + 49} * \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix}\\
&=\frac{1}{50} * \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 7 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \vec{v}
&=\frac{1}{50} \begin{pmatrix} \vec{v}_1 \\ \vec{v}_2 \end{pmatrix}
\end{align}
When we multiply back by $\vec{v}$ when multiplying by a matrix, we get it back. Therefore, multiplying everything by $\vec{v}$ as the multiplies gives us the projection matrix:
\begin{pmatrix} \frac{1}{50} & \frac{7}{50} \\ \frac{1}{50} & \frac{7}{50} \end{pmatrix}
</answer>

